I like this concept.
It's nice to turn the various enumeration strings into objects that can be confirmed at compile time. It is also nice that the strings can be associated to their respective XML, which can't be done with raw strings.
I was originally wary of the monolithic include file. Trying to find the correct item in a large blob of text may be daunting. In this case the XML file name helps zero in on the enum values. It also avoids the need to include svc-enums1.hpp, svc-enums-2.hpp, ... svc-enums-x.hpp. IMO that makes the large include file acceptable.

I can't find an argument to make against implementing this concept.

Thanks for the review!

I agree, I think there's a better way to breakdown the redfish_defs.h file into sub files without it devolving into a mess, and that's probably what I'll look at next.

I'm really looking for input on if the amount of magic in the nlohmann ifdefs is worth the cost of not being able to "read" the code, but it sounds like it is.

Take a look at what I just pushed.  I organized the enums by namespace (Sensor, Task, ect) IMO I think is a happy medium between header per enum and one giant header.  Take a look and see if that tracks for you.

Cool stuff! Yeah this has been a problem all over. I don't understand how this could lower the binary size. I would be okay if this increased the binary size slightly. We can discuss more after investigation.
Yep.  I also don't understand this I'm looking at it.
Turns out, the binary size isn't lower;  I either tricked myself, or new compilers optimize differently.  Commit message has the details.

The namespace plan looks like a good progression.
Will be interested to see how to add OEM schemas to the mix.

One of the existing OEM schemas is already handled for redfish-core/include/redfish_defs/oem_computer_system.hpp

This patch doesn't endeavor to solve the "we need generic OEM parameters" problem, but I don't think it makes it any worse.  In this context, OEM schemas aren't really "special"
Should you mark as WIP until testing / binary size are answered?
The commit message says it's WIP....  Not following what else we need.
Are these generated by some scripts or all by hand?
Since these are new files, should we start to follow the OpenBMC naming convention of enum members?

Yes, we should;  ACK.

Ideally someone should go look at how we can make clang-tidy enforce it at CI time.

actually, I wonder if this is a case where we shouldn't follow the openbmc naming convention.  Having the enums match the Redfish spec naming convention is allowed in our coding standard, and would improve in peoples ability to search for things, and recognize things in the standard.

WDYT?


Also, if we follow the naming standard, we're going to have to special case a lot of things.  For example, 

LDAPService

should arguably be

ldapService

in our naming convention, but there's no way to automatically determined that LDAP is an acronym in code, so we'd have to special case all the cases, which I don't think is worth the complexity.

https://redfish.dmtf.org/schemas/DSP0266_1.15.0.html#naming-rules

This makes sense to me. LdapService is better than LDAPService IMO.
LdapService is better to me as well, but that's not what DMTF did unfortunately.

They said

"Pascal-casing may be used for acronyms longer than two characters to improve readability, especially when two or more acronyms appear together in a name, which should be avoided."

LdapService is not banned.

Right, but regardless of what they allowed, the standard has LDAPService in it, and unfortunately, because of how standards compliance and backward compatibility work, we don't really want to change it just for the sake of naming.  This is different than code, where it's pretty easy to rename a variable that isn't in an external facing library.
Why do we need NOLINT here?

our clang-tidy rules disallow macros, but in this case, it's a macro in a library we don't maintain, so it's allowed.

I can mention this in the commit message.

ACK.

Arguably should go in another commit.  I'll move it to one.  ACK

this is undefined behavior because toReadingUnits returns a const char*.  If you then capture by std::string&, you now have a reference to a destroyed rvalue.

The fact that this code works means that the undefined behavior is swinging in our favor, but it might not forever.

const std::string& is not undefined. Lifetime of temporary object is extended. You can read more about it here:

https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/language/reference (ctrl+f 
Rvalue references)

Nit,
Have you thought about turning this into a library, and created a new openbmc repo to house this code base?

Just enum generation doesn't really seem useful in that context, but maybe combined with your type safe structures patch, it might be a good replacement to https://github.com/DMTF/Redfish-Schema-C-Struct-Generator.  Something to think about for sure;  If you know of other things that would use this stuff, that's something we could talk about in the future.  I'm happy to rip this patch out and request a separate repo if there's another user, but I don't want to maintain that level of version-to-version compatibility without a user.

Usb -> USB
Hdd -> HDD
Cd -> CD
Pxe - > PXE

These are correct to the redfish standard:

https://redfish.dmtf.org/schemas/ComputerSystem_v1.xml

In the other thread, we discussed changing the casing, and decided it wasn't worth the effort, and inconsistency with the spec, and that we should be naming these the same as the spec to be consistent (and to improve the readability).

Is there a reason these specific ones should change?

In the cable enum it cased all caps, and most of the acronyms are cased correctly. If the spec has this inconstancy then it is fine in the implementation.  

https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/bmcweb/+/51993/15/redfish-core/include/redfish_defs/cable.hpp#39

(resolved)

Have you considered generating conertion functions or just create template function that can perform any conversion. It would be possible to take conversion map and string value as parameter. Perform find, return value if success or empty optional/invalid on failure.

That could remove some code, but I don't know if this going to decrease or increase binary size.

> Have you considered generating conertion functions or just create template function that can perform any conversion.

Yes.  This was all evaluated by someone previously on your team (Pawel), and the conclusion at the time what that essentially anything else we tried resulted in slower builds, larger binaries, and longer runtimes.  That was done several years ago, so we could certainly reassess with current technology and our now better understanding of what dbus->redfish conversions need done.

The biggest problem becomes that most dbus->redfish conversions are not as clean as this one.  There are cases where:
- New enums are added without bmcweb being made aware.
- two dbus enum values might map to one redfish value.
- one dbus property might map to multiple redfish values in odd ways (Status is a good example of this).

All of those cases need to be able to be handled.

> It would be possible to take conversion map and string value as parameter. Perform find, return value if success or empty optional/invalid on failure.

When we tried this, we either needed to declare a runtime std::map which we could either construct on global init, or construct on each use.  In the former it slowed the boot time, and used runtime memory (against some of the core bmcweb principles).  In the latter case, it was significantly slower to construct the map, do the lookup on the map, then destroy the map each time it was used.

Since we did that testing, boost::describe was added into boost, which might solve some of these issues in a cleaner way, but that would need to be evaluated.  What nlohmann implements is essentially similar to what boost describe does, but specializes it for json values.

> 
> That could remove some code, but I don't know if this going to decrease or increase binary size.

Happy to see test results if you're interested in pursuing this.

So you are adding "Invalid" to every enum that does not have it?
Does this make sense, will there be enums that have similar error states such as (unknown, or Error)
sometimes "Invalid" will be enum invalid, and some time it will be a spec defined "Invalid"

Sorry, missed this comment initially.  The enums need a state for "Unable to parse string into a valid enumeration" for when we get an invalid string from the user.  From my perspective, I thought that "Invalid" made sense, and this check was just for sanity testing to make sure we didn't end up with duplicates that caused compiler errors.  I don't think any Redfish Enums declare an invalid state, so I don't think there's a conflict, but I'm open to changing to something else if you think there's a way to make this more clear.  Can you sketch out what you think would make sense in this context?  It's not very clear from either message.

gotcha, because there are no current uses of "Invalid" as an enum value it is not as serious an issue.

If the state were"_InvalidEnumField" we would be far less likely to have collisions.

Let's say there was a future enum that wanted to include "Invalid" as a value.  I'm not sure it would be an issue if we overload "Invalid" so that it also means we didn't find a valid value.  I'm assuming that new enum would use "Invalid" in the same way that this patch in places like sensors.hpp is using "Invalid".

this "invalid" => "Unable to parse string into a valid enumeration" 
One could imagine scenarios in which the state of something is invalid


You could imagine an enum like
CertificateStatus ={Authorized, authenticated, NoAuth ... Invalid}, 
one might want to do different things if the enum is invalid, then if a cert is Invalid. 

But I don't feel too strongly about this.

> Let's say there was a future enum that wanted to include "Invalid" as a value.

In the very unlikely case that Redfish backpedaled, and started using the "Invalid" keyword on their enums, we could pretty easily just find/replace to a different word.  I don't think whatever decision we make here will be fatal.

>  I'm assuming that new enum would use "Invalid" in the same way that this patch in places like sensors.hpp is using "Invalid".

I don't expect any code to actually use Invalid, except for comparisons for "string couldn't be converted to a valid enum".


> One could imagine scenarios in which the state of something is invalid

Right, which would go into status codes.  An individual property cannot be invalid in Redfish.


> CertificateStatus ={Authorized, authenticated, NoAuth ... Invalid}, 

See above.  If Redfish decides to start using the enum "invalid" it's a trivial find and replace to swap "invalid" for "new word that we pick later".  I feel pretty strongly that this isn't going to give us a step backwards.
I'm good with Ed's explanation and leaving it as is.

IMO it is worth the increase in binary size. 
I have seen a fair amount of bugs with these Redfish enums, and I think they will continue in the future (e.g., I have seen multiple simple bugs around spelling and capitalization of Redfish Enums).
This is also another thing reviewers don't have to worry as much about.  

This adds more files and another generate script, but I think the pros outweigh the cons (with the main con being the increase in binary size).

Full disclosure, IBM is less concerned with binary size due to larger flash on its latest machines. The mailing would give companies a chance to object..?

> IMO it is worth the increase in binary size. 

+1.  I should also mention that every time I do the measurement, I get a different answer.  It's so far in the noise that it almost doesn't matter and depends very heavily on compiler versions and generated code compression complexity.

Question for those looking at this thread.  Is "redfish_defs" a good enough name?  It seems mediocre to me, but I couldn't come up with a better one creatively.
What about something like "enums", "redfish_enums", or "enum_defs"?  I'd kinda like some form of "enum" in the name, but it's not that big of a deal.

Maybe "generated".  My thinking with that is that:
"we're already in the redfish-core folder, so adding "redfish" again doesn't add value"

?

What's the plan of updating all redfish-core codes? All at once, incrementally?

As with most things, incrementally.  Where we're able, we try to avoid "big bang" type changes.  With these enums, I think the existing code can be moved over incrementally over time, although we could likely come up with a few large commits that moves basically everything over, but I'd like us to get a little experience with these first.
